            <div>
                <h3>History</h3>
                <p>
                    Biñan City began as a small agricultural settlement along Laguna de Bay before Spanish colonization and officially became a town in 1571 under Spanish rule, growing into an important farming and trading center during the colonial period; it is also historically significant as a place associated with national hero José Rizal, who studied there in his youth, and over time Biñan transformed from a rural pueblo into a modern industrial and commercial hub, eventually achieving cityhood in 2010 while retaining its cultural and historical heritage.
                    
                    During the American and Japanese periods, Biñan City continued to develop as an agricultural and residential town while also experiencing the hardships of World War II, after which it steadily modernized with improved education, transportation, and local governance; in the late 20th century, rapid industrialization and urban growth transformed Biñan into a key economic center in Laguna, blending its historical roots with progress and preparing it for its official conversion into a component city in the 21st century.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div>
            <div> image container </div>
            <div>
                <h3>Heritage</h3>
                <p>
                    Biñan City is rich in cultural and historical heritage shaped by its deep ties to Philippine nationalism and colonial history. One of its most important heritage landmarks is the ancestral home of José Rizal’s family, where the national hero spent part of his childhood and received early education. The city also preserves Spanish-era influences through old churches, traditional houses, and long-standing religious festivals that reflect the strong Catholic faith and community spirit of its people.
                    Beyond historical sites, Biñan’s heritage lives on in its traditions, local crafts, and annual celebrations such as the Puto Latik Festival, which honors its famous rice delicacy and agricultural roots. These customs highlight the city’s identity as a place of hard work, resilience, and pride in local culture. As Biñan continues to grow into a modern urban center, efforts to protect its historical landmarks and traditions ensure that its heritage remains an important part of daily life and future generations.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div>
            <div> image container </div>
            <div>
                <h3>Facts</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        José Rizal studied under Maestro Justiniano Aquino Cruz in Biñan, where he experienced his first fight and first lessons in Latin and Spanish—shaping his early character and discipline.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Biñan was once one of the wealthiest towns in Laguna during the Spanish era because of its vast rice fields and sugarcane plantations.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        The city’s famous Puto Biñan (Puto Latik) is steamed in special clay molds, giving it a unique taste and texture different from ordinary puto found elsewhere.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Biñan sits along an old trade route between Manila and southern Luzon, making it historically important for commerce even before highways existed.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        During World War II, parts of Biñan were used by guerrilla fighters as hiding and meeting places against Japanese forces.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        The Rizal family’s home in Biñan is considered one of the earliest “classrooms” of the national hero before he entered Ateneo Municipal.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Biñan transformed faster than many Laguna towns because it became a gateway city between Metro Manila and CALABARZON’s industrial zones.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Despite modernization, some barangays still practice old traditions like community cooking for fiestas and religious processions dating back to Spanish times.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        The city’s seal and symbols reflect both agriculture (rice and farming tools) and education, showing its dual identity of labor and learning.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Biñan is one of the few Philippine cities that blends Rizal heritage, food culture, and industrial growth into a single historical narrative.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
